## First-deploy bootstrap: detect + fix app SP self-permission chicken-and-egg

Context: On a freshly-deployed Databricks App, the app's own service
principal is not granted any permission on the app it runs. As a result,
`GET /api/2.0/permissions/apps/{name}` returns 403 when the middleware
tries to read the ACL, `list_app_principals` silently returns empty, and
the first request — even from a `CAN_MANAGE` deployer — is redirected to
`/access-denied?reason=app`. The only fix was to manually grant the SP
CAN_MANAGE on its own app, which is non-obvious and happens every time
the app is re-created.

Changes:

1. scripts/bootstrap-app-permissions.sh (NEW) — idempotent helper that
   resolves each app's `service_principal_client_id` via
   `databricks apps get` and calls `databricks apps update-permissions`
   to grant `CAN_MANAGE` on itself. Defaults to both `ontobricks` and
   `mcp-ontobricks`; accepts app name(s) as arguments. Safe to re-run.
2. scripts/deploy.sh — runs the bootstrap script automatically after
   `bundle run`, so a standard `make deploy` leaves the app fully
   accessible on first load. The existing MCP → main cross-grant step
   was renumbered from 7 to 8.
3. Makefile — added `make bootstrap-perms` target for manual invocation
   (e.g., when deploying via `databricks bundle deploy` directly).
4. src/back/core/databricks/WorkspaceService.py — `list_app_principals`
   now records the HTTP status code of the REST call on
   `self._last_app_permissions_status` (exposed as a read-only
   property). 403 is no longer indistinguishable from an empty ACL.
5. src/back/core/databricks/DatabricksClient.py — forwards the new
   `last_app_permissions_status` property from the underlying
   `WorkspaceService`.
6. src/back/objects/registry/permissions.py — `PermissionService` now
   inspects the status after every `list_app_principals` call and sets
   `_app_principals_forbidden = True` when it was 403. Exposed via
   `is_app_principals_forbidden()`. `clear_principals_cache()` also
   clears the flag.
7. src/shared/fastapi/main.py — `PermissionMiddleware` imports
   `permission_service` and, when blocking a `ROLE_NONE` request,
   consults `is_app_principals_forbidden()`. If true, redirects to
   `/access-denied?reason=bootstrap` (instead of `reason=app`) and logs
   a warning pointing at the bootstrap script.
8. src/front/routes/home.py — `/access-denied` accepts the new
   `reason=bootstrap` value; invalid reasons fall back to `app`.
9. src/front/templates/access_denied.html — dedicated message for
   `reason=bootstrap` with a `make bootstrap-perms` snippet and a
   brief explanation of the chicken-and-egg problem.
10. README.md — added a "First deploy only" callout under the Deploy
    section pointing at `make deploy` (auto) and `make bootstrap-perms`
    (manual fallback).
11. docs/deployment.md — rewrote the "How Admin Detection Works"
    section to be accurate about SP self-permission requirements and
    added a new "First-Deploy Bootstrap" subsection.

Tests:

12. tests/test_permissions.py — added `TestAppPrincipalsBootstrap`
    (4 tests) covering: 200 clears the flag, 403 sets it, non-403
    errors (e.g. 500) do not set it, and `clear_principals_cache`
    resets it.
13. tests/test_permission_middleware.py — added two tests under
    `TestRoleEnforcement`: HTML request with `ROLE_NONE` +
    non-forbidden principals → 302 with `reason=app`; HTML request
    with `ROLE_NONE` + `is_app_principals_forbidden=True` → 302 with
    `reason=bootstrap`.

